Family & Diversity:
       Trout belong to the Salmonidae family and include species like rainbow trout, brown trout, and brook trout. They are genetically diverse and highly adaptable.

Habitat:
       They thrive in cold, clear freshwater environments such as rivers, lakes, and streams across North America, Europe, and Asia.

Diet:
       Trout are carnivorous and feed on insects, small fish, and crustaceans. Larger trout can consume surprisingly big prey.

Life Cycle:
       Most trout spawn in gravel-bottomed streams. Their lifecycle includes egg, alevin, fry, juvenile, and adult stages.

Migration:
       Some species, like sea trout, migrate between freshwater and saltwater. Others remain in freshwater their entire lives.

Ecological Role:
       Trout are key indicators of water quality and play a vital role in aquatic ecosystems by maintaining balance in food chains.

Cultural & Culinary Value: 
       Trout are prized in sport fishing and are considered a delicacy in many cuisines due to their mild flavor and nutritional value.
